{"title_page": "Outline of environmental journalism", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Overview of and topical guide to environmental journalism}}\n<!--... Attention:  THIS IS AN OUTLINE\n\n        part of the set of 740+ outlines listed at\n             [[Portal:Contents/Outlines]].\n\n                 Wikipedia outlines are\n              a special type of list article.\n              They make up one of Wikipedia's\n                content navigation systems\n\n                See [[Wikipedia:Outlines]]\n                      for more details.\n                   Further improvements\n              to this outline are on the way\n...-->\nThe following [[Outline (list)|outline]] is provided as an overview of and topical guide to environmental journalism:\n\n'''[[Environmental journalism]]''' &ndash; collection, verification, production, distribution and exhibition of information regarding current events, trends, issues and people that are associated with the non-human world. It is closely related to, and probably grew from, [[nature writing]] and [[environmental communication]]. Key points environmental journalism focuses on are [[global warming]] and [[ecology]].\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Essence==\n* [[Nature writing]]\n* [[Environmental communication]]\n* [[Ecology]]\n\n==Branches==\n\n* [[Nature writing]]\n* [[Science writing]]\n* [[Environmental journalism#Environmental literature|Environmental literature]]\n\n==Common topics==\n* [[Agriculture]]\n* [[Air Pollution]]\n* [[Biodiversity]]\n* [[Cancer]]\n* [[Chemical weapons]]\n* [[Children]]'s [[Health]] ([[Asthma]])\n* [[Dioxins and dioxin-like compounds]]\n* [[Ecosystems]]\n* [[Endocrine Disruptors]]\n* [[Environmental Justice]]\n* [[Food irradiation]]\n* [[Genetically Modified Crops]]\n* [[Global warming|Global Warming]] / [[Climate change (general concept)|Climate Change]]\n* [[Occupational Health]]\n* [[Ozone]]\n* [[Pesticides]]\n* [[Population growth]]\n* [[Urban sprawl|Sprawl]] / [[Environmental Health]]\n\n==History==\n<!-- This section needs links to articles -->\n\n==General concepts==\n\n* [[Environmentalism]]\n* [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]] (Closely tied with Environmentalism)\n* [[Environmental reporting]]\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Expand section|date=November 2009}}\n* [[Nirmal Shah]]\n* [[Rachel Carson]]\n\n==Environmental==\n* [[List of environmental topics]]\n* [[List of environmental periodicals]]\n* [[List of environmental publications]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment}}\n* [[Environment (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Journalism]]\n* [[Heritage interpretation]]\n* [[:Category:Natural environment]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sej.org/ Society of Environmental Journalists]\n{{Sister project links|Environmental journalism}}\n\n{{outline footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Journalism}}\n[[Category:Outlines of human activities]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia outlines]]\n[[Category:Environmental mass media]]\n[[Category:Journalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Overview of and topical guide to environmental journalism}}\n<!--... Attention:  THIS IS AN OUTLINE\n\n        part of the set of 740+ outlines listed at\n             [[Portal:Contents/Outlines]].\n\n                 Wikipedia outlines are\n              a special type of list article.\n              They make up one of Wikipedia's\n                content navigation systems\n\n                See [[Wikipedia:Outlines]]\n                      for more details.\n                   Further improvements\n              to this outline are on the way\n...-->\nThe following [[Outline (list)|outline]] is provided as an overview of and topical guide to environmental journalism:\n\n'''[[Environmental journalism]]''' &ndash; collection, verification, production, distribution and exhibition of information regarding current events, trends, issues and people that are associated with the non-human world. It is closely related to, and probably grew from, [[nature writing]] and [[environmental communication]]. Key points environmental journalism focuses on are [[global warming]] and [[ecology]].\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Essence==\n* [[Nature writing]]\n* [[Environmental communication]]\n* [[Ecology]]\n\n==Branches==\n\n* [[Nature writing]]\n* [[Science writing]]\n* [[Environmental journalism#Environmental literature|Environmental literature]]\n\n==Common topics==\n* [[Agriculture]]\n* [[Air Pollution]]\n* [[Biodiversity]]\n* [[Cancer]]\n* [[Chemical weapons]]\n* [[Children]]'s [[Health]] ([[Asthma]])\n* [[Dioxins and dioxin-like compounds]]\n* [[Ecosystems]]\n* [[Endocrine Disruptors]]\n* [[Environmental Justice]]\n* [[Food irradiation]]\n* [[Genetically Modified Crops]]\n* [[Global Warming]] / [[Climate Change]]\n* [[Occupational Health]]\n* [[Ozone]]\n* [[Pesticides]]\n* [[Population growth]]\n* [[Urban sprawl|Sprawl]] / [[Environmental Health]]\n\n==History==\n<!-- This section needs links to articles -->\n\n==General concepts==\n\n* [[Environmentalism]]\n* [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]] (Closely tied with Environmentalism)\n* [[Environmental reporting]]\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Expand section|date=November 2009}}\n* [[Nirmal Shah]]\n* [[Rachel Carson]]\n\n==Environmental==\n* [[List of environmental topics]]\n* [[List of environmental periodicals]]\n* [[List of environmental publications]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment}}\n* [[Environment (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Journalism]]\n* [[Heritage interpretation]]\n* [[:Category:Natural environment]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sej.org/ Society of Environmental Journalists]\n{{Sister project links|Environmental journalism}}\n\n{{outline footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Journalism}}\n[[Category:Outlines of human activities]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia outlines]]\n[[Category:Environmental mass media]]\n[[Category:Journalism]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Global Warming\u2192Global warming,Climate Change\u2192Climate change (general concept)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outline_of_environmental_journalism"}
{"title_page": "Pigpile", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Pigpile\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Big Black]]\n| cover      = Big Black - Pigpile cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1992|10|05}}\n| recorded   = 1987\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=46|s=02}}\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Songs About Fucking]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Pigpile''''' is a live recording from July 24, 1987 during the [[post-hardcore]] band [[Big Black]]'s final European tour, released originally as a [[VHS]] tape (it was their second video release, following the 'Live' tape on Atavistic Records.) and later issued as an audio-only LP/CD. The recordings were made at the Hammersmith Clarendon concert hall, [[London]]. A 5\" transparent heavy-duty vinyl record was included away free with all copies of the VHS tape and some copies of the soundtrack album, featuring a [[cover version]] of the [[Mary Jane Girls]] song \"In My House\". Lower-quality recordings from the Hammersmith concert had previously appeared in a different configuartion on the [[bootleg recording|bootleg]] LP ''Tonight We Walked With Giants''.\n\n''Pigpile'' coincided with the re-release of Big Black's entire catalog on [[Touch and Go Records|Touch-and-Go]] Records A limited edition of ''Pigpile'' was issued as a box set that included the LP and its insert, a VHS tape of the Hammersmith concert, the \"In My House\" one-sided 5\" single, a poster and a Big Black T-shirt.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone, 2001\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Bashe |editor1-first=Patricia Romanowski |editor2-last=Pareles |editor2-first=Jon |editor3-last=George-Warren |editor3-first=Holly |title=Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll: Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll |date=2001 |publisher=Touchstone |isbn=978-0-7432-0120-9 |page=72 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=allmusic ((( ''Pigpile'' > Review )))|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r71104|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|author=Raggett, Ned|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>Brackett, Nathan. \"Big Black\". ''The New Rolling Stone Album Guide''. November 2004. pg. 69, cited March 17, 2010</ref>\n}}\n\nReleased five years after Big Black chose to disband at the peak of their artistic and commercial success, ''Pigpile'' received concurrent and retrospective reviews ranging from lukewarm to gushing. Writing shortly after the album's release, ''[[Spin Magazine]]'' remarked that ''Pigpile'' was \"a live album with sound quality unworthy of an audio nut like Albini.\"<ref name=\"Spin, 1995\">{{cite book |last1=Weisbard |first1=Eric |last2=Marks |first2=Craig |title=Spin Alternative Record Guide |date=1995 |publisher=Vintage Books |isbn=978-0-679-75574-6 |language=en}}</ref> Looking back at Albini's career through Big Black and his subsequent band, [[Rapeman]] a decade on, ''Rolling Stone'' called ''Pigpile'' a \"fun-but-not-revelatory live album,\" ranking it a notch below any of the group's studio albums.\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"Fists of Love\"  \u2013 4:14\n# \"L Dopa\"  \u2013 1:49\n# \"Passing Complexion\"  \u2013 3:06\n# \"Dead Billy\"  \u2013 5:12\n# \"Cables\"  \u2013 3:18\n# \"Bad Penny\"  \u2013 3:03\n# \"Pavement Saw\"  \u2013 2:56\n# \"Kerosene\"  \u2013 6:38\n# \"Steelworker\"  \u2013 4:52\n# \"Pigeon Kill\"  \u2013 2:24\n# \"Fish Fry\"  \u2013 1:55\n# \"Jordan, Minnesota\"  \u2013 7:05\n\n==Album credits==\n*[[Big Black]] - Performance\n*[[Steve Albini]] - Inlay Notes\n*Cheryl Graham - Album Artwork\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Big Black}}\n\n[[Category:Big Black albums]]\n[[Category:1992 live albums]]\n[[Category:Touch and Go Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Au Go Go Records live albums]]\n\n{{1990s-punk-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Pigpile\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Big Black]]\n| cover      = Big Black - Pigpile cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1992|10|05}}\n| recorded   = 1987\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=46|s=02}}\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Songs About Fucking]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Pigpile''''' is a live recording from July 24, 1987 during the [[post-hardcore]] band [[Big Black]]'s final European tour, released originally as a [[VHS]] tape (it was their second video release, following the 'Live' tape on Atavistic Records.) and later issued as an audio-only LP/CD. The recordings were made at the Hammersmith Clarendon concert hall, [[London]]. A 5\" transparent heavy-duty vinyl record was included away free with all copies of the VHS tape and some copies of the soundtrack album, featuring a [[cover version]] of the [[Mary Jane Girls]] song \"In My House\". Lower-quality recordings from the Hammersmith concert had previously appeared in a different configuartion on the [[bootleg]] LP ''Tonight We Walked With Giants''.\n\n''Pigpile'' coincided with the re-release of Big Black's entire catalog on [[Touch-and-Go]] Records A limited edition of ''Pigpile'' was issued as a box set that included the LP and its insert, a VHS tape of the Hammersmith concert, the \"In My House\" one-sided 5\" single, a poster and a Big Black T-shirt.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone, 2001\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Bashe |editor1-first=Patricia Romanowski |editor2-last=Pareles |editor2-first=Jon |editor3-last=George-Warren |editor3-first=Holly |title=Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll: Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll |date=2001 |publisher=Touchstone |isbn=978-0-7432-0120-9 |page=72 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=allmusic ((( ''Pigpile'' > Review )))|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r71104|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|author=Raggett, Ned|accessdate=March 17, 2010}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>Brackett, Nathan. \"Big Black\". ''The New Rolling Stone Album Guide''. November 2004. pg. 69, cited March 17, 2010</ref>\n}}\n\nReleased five years after Big Black chose to disband at the peak of their artistic and commercial success, ''Pigpile'' received concurrent and retrospective reviews ranging from lukewarm to gushing. Writing shortly after the album's release, ''[[Spin Magazine]]'' remarked that ''Pigpile'' was \"a live album with sound quality unworthy of an audio nut like Albini.\"<ref name=\"Spin, 1995\">{{cite book |last1=Weisbard |first1=Eric |last2=Marks |first2=Craig |title=Spin Alternative Record Guide |date=1995 |publisher=Vintage Books |isbn=978-0-679-75574-6 |language=en}}</ref> Looking back at Albini's career through Big Black and his subsequent band, [[Rapeman]] a decade on, ''Rolling Stone'' called ''Pigpile'' a \"fun-but-not-revelatory live album,\" ranking it a notch below any of the group's studio albums.\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"Fists of Love\"  \u2013 4:14\n# \"L Dopa\"  \u2013 1:49\n# \"Passing Complexion\"  \u2013 3:06\n# \"Dead Billy\"  \u2013 5:12\n# \"Cables\"  \u2013 3:18\n# \"Bad Penny\"  \u2013 3:03\n# \"Pavement Saw\"  \u2013 2:56\n# \"Kerosene\"  \u2013 6:38\n# \"Steelworker\"  \u2013 4:52\n# \"Pigeon Kill\"  \u2013 2:24\n# \"Fish Fry\"  \u2013 1:55\n# \"Jordan, Minnesota\"  \u2013 7:05\n\n==Album credits==\n*[[Big Black]] - Performance\n*[[Steve Albini]] - Inlay Notes\n*Cheryl Graham - Album Artwork\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Big Black}}\n\n[[Category:Big Black albums]]\n[[Category:1992 live albums]]\n[[Category:Touch and Go Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Au Go Go Records live albums]]\n\n{{1990s-punk-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:bootleg\u2192bootleg recording,Touch-and-Go\u2192Touch and Go Records", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pigpile"}
{"title_page": "Ben Cousins", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer, born 1978}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Ben Cousins\n| image = Ben Cousins.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Cousins with West Coast in 2006\n| fullname = Benjamin Luke Cousins\n| nickname = Cuz, Prince of Perth\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|6|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = Bullcreek-Leeming JFC\n| draftpick = [[Father-Son Rule|Father/son selection]], [[1995 AFL Draft|1995]] <small>({{AFL WC}})</small><br />6th overall, [[2008 AFL Draft#2009 Pre-season Draft|2009 Pre-season Draft]] <small>({{AFL Ric}})</small>\n| height = 179 cm<!--automatic conversion--><ref name=\"richmondfc.com.au\">{{cite web |url=http://www.richmondfc.com.au/players/playerprofile/tabid/8473/default.aspx?playerid=19974&typeid=2 |title=Player profile |accessdate=10 May 2009 |publisher=Richmond Football Club |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090622034432/http://www.richmondfc.com.au/players/playerprofile/tabid/8473/default.aspx?playerid=19974&typeid=2 |archivedate=22 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| weight = 78 kg<!--automatic conversion--><ref name=\"richmondfc.com.au\" />\n| position = Midfielder\n| statsend = 2010\n| repstatsend = 1999\n| years1 = 1996\u20132007\n| club1 = {{AFL WC}}\n| games_goals1 = 238 (205)\n| years2 = 2009\u20132010\n| club2 = {{AFL Ric}}\n| games_goals2 = {{0}}32 {{0}}(12)\n| games_goalstotal = 270 (217)\n| nationalyears1 = 1999\n| nationalteam1 = [[Australian International rules football team|Australia]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 = 2 (0)\n| careerhighlights = * [[AFL Rising Star]]: (1996)\n* 6x [[All-Australian Team]]: (1998, 1999, 2001, 2002, 2005, 2006)\n* [[AFL Goal of the Year|Goal of the Year]]: (1999)\n* [[International Rules Series]]: (1999)\n* {{AFL WC}} [[List of captains of the West Coast Eagles|Captain]]: (2001 (co-captain), 2002\u201305)\n* 4x [[John Worsfold Medal|West Coast Club Champion]]: (2001, 2002, 2003, 2005)\n* [[Geoff Christian Medal]]: (2001)\n* {{AFL WC}} Life Member: (2003)\n* [[Brownlow Medal]]: ([[2005 Brownlow Medal|2005]])\n* [[Leigh Matthews Trophy]]: (2005)\n* [[Western Australian Sports Star of the Year]]: (2005)\n* {{AFL WC}} [[West Coast Eagles#Team 20|Team 20]]: (2006)\n* {{AFL WC}} Premiership Player: ([[2006 AFL Grand Final|2006]])\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Luke Cousins''' (born 30 June 1978<ref>{{cite news |title=Cousins and Cats: so nearly |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/05/07/1052280325389.html |work=The Age |date=8 May 2003 |accessdate=21 December 2008 |location=Australia}}</ref>) is a former professional [[Australian rules football]]er who played for {{AFL WC}} and {{AFL Ric}} in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL).\n\nCousins is listed by journalist [[Mike Sheahan]] as one of the fifty greatest players of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afl.com.au/tabid/208/default.aspx?newsid=55909 |title=Mike Sheahan\u2019s top 50 players |date=6 March 2008 |accessdate=28 March 2012 |publisher=Australian Football League}}</ref> During his 12-year, 238-game career with West Coast, he won several of the league's highest individual awards, including a [[Brownlow Medal]], [[Leigh Matthews Trophy|Most Valuable Player]] and a [[premiership medallion]]. He was also selected six times in the [[All-Australian Team]] and represented [[Australia international rules football team|Australia]] in the [[International Rules Series]]. He was West Coast's [[West Coast Eagles Club Champion Award|club champion]] for four seasons and [[List of captains of the West Coast Eagles|captain]] for five seasons.\n\nCousins' football career was marred by highly publicised off-field incidents involving [[recreational drug use]], traffic convictions and association with criminal elements. On several occasions he was fined or sanctioned by West Coast, culminating in his contract's termination in October 2007.<ref name=sacked>{{cite news |title=Magistrate adjourns case and allows Eagle rehab trip |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22601779-952,00.html |work=The Courier-Mail |date=18 October 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> The following month, he was banned from AFL for one year by the [[AFL Commission]] for \"bringing the game into disrepute\".<ref name=\"disrepute\">{{cite news |title=Cousins banned by AFL for 12 months |url=http://news.realfooty.com.au/sport/cousins-banned-by-afl-for-12-months-20071119-1b9l.html |work=Real Footy |date=19 November 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> Amid predictions that he would remain undrafted, Richmond claimed Cousins with the last pick of the [[2008 AFL Draft|2008 draft]]. He played 32 games across two seasons at the club, retiring from the AFL at the end of the [[2010 AFL season|2010 season]].\n\nCousins co-produced a documentary film titled ''[[Such is Life: The Troubled Times of Ben Cousins]]'', saying he hoped it would serve as a cautionary tale against drug use. Released days after his retirement, it went onto become \"one of the most-watched documentaries in Australian history.\"<ref name=toohey>Toohey, Paul (18 September 2010). [https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/national/a-perth-funeral-that-triggered-that-cousins-doco/news-story/5ab3702a4f36a3229047a9450a31a99e \"A Perth funeral that triggered that Cousins doco\"], ''Adelaide Now''. Retrieved 7 July 2018.</ref> Post-football, Cousins continued to struggle with his drug addiction and have run-ins with the law, and in 2017 he received a 12-month prison sentence for a variety of offences.\n\n==Early life==\nCousins was born in [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], in 1978, to Stephanie and [[Bryan Cousins|Bryan]], an [[Australian rules football]]er who had moved from [[Western Australia]] to play for the [[Geelong Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]]. When Cousins was 18 months old, his family moved back to [[Perth]], Western Australia,<ref name=\"sweeney\">{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Sweeney |title=Fastest gun in the west |work=Sunday Herald Sun |date=25 July 1999 |page=13}}</ref> where he was raised with younger siblings Matthew, Sophie and Melanie. He played junior football for the Bull Creek-Leeming Junior Football Club<ref>{{cite news |first=Craig |last=O'Donoghue |title=Bull Creek Australia's top junior club |work=The West Australian |date=12 June 2004 |page=182}}</ref> and for his private school, [[Wesley College, Perth|Wesley College]]. In his last year at Wesley in 1995, he was recruited to join the [[East Fremantle Football Club]]'s senior side in the [[West Australian Football League]] (WAFL) and played for both his school and East Fremantle throughout the season.<ref name=\"sweeney\" />\n\nWhile Cousins was still at school, three AFL teams competed to draft him under the [[father\u2013son rule]]: the Geelong Football Club, the [[West Coast Eagles]], and the newly formed [[Fremantle Football Club]]. Cousins' father Bryan played 238 games for [[Perth Football Club|Perth]] in the WAFL and 67 games for Geelong in the VFL during the 1970s and 1980s. Geelong's recruiting manager, Stephen Wells, said, \"Ben barracked for Geelong and we tried everything to get him here.\"<ref name=\"sweeney\" /> However, Cousins preferred to remain based in Western Australia and chose West Coast in October 1995.\n\n==AFL career==\n\n===West Coast Eagles===\n====1996\u20131997: Rising Star Award and increasing popularity====\nAt 17, a week after his tenth WAFL game for East Fremantle, Cousins played his first AFL match and kicked two goals for West Coast against Geelong.<ref name=\"sweeney\" /> He won the [[Norwich Rising Star]] award for his debut season in 1996, polling 15 votes from the six judges to beat [[Shannon Grant]] by one point.<ref>{{cite news |first=Malcolm |last=Conn |title=Rising star wants to stay put |work=The Australian |date=11 September 1996 |page=22}}</ref>\n\nCousins' popularity continued to increase over the following seasons. In 1998, the ''[[Herald Sun]]'' ran a two-page article across its centre pages about 20-year-old Cousins, titled \"West goes wild for the kid\". The article portrayed Cousins as a [[sex symbol]] and \"football's answer to [[Brad Pitt]]\". When asked about the article, he said the popularity \"comes with the territory... If you want to be a league footballer you have to accept that it is part of the game.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=McGrath |title=Cousins lives up to the publicity |work=The West Australian |date=27 July 1998 |page=6}}</ref> Sports agent [[Ricky Nixon]] approached Cousins in 1998 about managing his endorsement deals, because \"He's good-looking, he elected to stay in Perth and not play in Victoria, opposition coaches take notice of him and on top of that he's a future leader.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Casellas |title=Ben no longer a bargain |work=The West Australian |date=22 October 1998 |page=2}}</ref> In 1999, [[International Management Group]], who managed sports stars such as [[Tiger Woods]] and [[Pete Sampras]], said they would like to sign Ben, as \"There is no doubt that he is now in the top bracket of players and has great marketing potential... Apart from being an outstanding footballer, he is a quality young man.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=McGrath |title=IMG has sights on Cousins |work=The West Australian |date=22 June 1999 |page=76}}</ref> Ross Nicholas, West Coast's marketing manager, said:<ref name=\"sweeney\" />\n\n<blockquote>\"He's easily the most sought-after Eagle... No player was, or is, as popular as Ben. His appeal is so diverse. Kids want his autograph and photograph. Sponsors want him to sit next to them. They want him to push their product... If Ben's well managed, the sky's the limit for him... They've got to find the balance between his commercial potential and his contribution to the community. The club offers protection, but it's up to Ben what demands he puts himself under.\"</blockquote>\n\n====1997\u20132000: First finals appearance and first All-Australian selection====\nIn 1998, Cousins was selected in the [[All-Australian Team]] and was runner-up in West Coast's [[West Coast Eagles Club Champion Award|Best and Fairest]].<ref name=\"hero\">{{cite news |title=Ben Cousins: hero |work=The West Australian |date=2 April 2002}}</ref> He played in his first AFL finals game in 1999, against the [[Western Bulldogs]] in a qualifying final at the [[MCG]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davis |title=Captain Cousins for sure |work=The Australian |date=11 September 1999 |page=61}}</ref> and the year included another selection in the All-Australian Team and representing [[Australian international rules football team|Australia]] in the [[International Rules Series]].<ref name=\"hero\" /> In 2000, Cousins signed a new three-year contract with the West Coast Eagles, reportedly worth nearly A$1&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"coghlan\">{{cite news |first=Scott |last=Coghlan |title=Captaincy next for Cousins |work=The Australian |date=5 August 2000 |page=55}}</ref>\n\n====2000\u20132003: Best and Fairest at West Coast and appointed co-captain====\nHe played his 100th game amid speculation he would take over the captaincy from [[Guy McKenna]], who was due to retire after the same game. Cousins said, \"After you play two or three seasons, you think of the possibility of a leadership role down the track, but the talk of it has certainly come a lot earlier than I would have thought.\"<ref name=\"coghlan\" /> In 2001, Cousins was named co-[[List of captains of the West Coast Eagles|captain]], sharing the role with [[Dean Kemp]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Young Eagle jumps Jako |work=Herald Sun |date=8 February 2001 |page=98}}</ref> He won his first club Best and Fairest at the end of the season, a feat which he repeated in 2002 and 2003,<ref name=\"connolly\">{{cite news |first=Rohan |last=Connolly |title=Bred to win a Brownlow |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=20 September 2005 |page=2}}</ref> and he was again named in the All-Australian Team in 2001 and 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Cousins |work=The West Australian |date=15 July 2005 |page=6}}</ref> Kemp's retirement saw Cousins become the captain in 2002, a role he filled until 2006. In 2005, West Coast coach [[John Worsfold]] said of Cousins' fifth year as captain, \"Ben is improving all the time and with the way this group is coming along, I think he is going to be a great leader\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Butler |title=Eagles stick with leadership |work=The West Australian |date=3 February 2005 |page=63}}</ref>\n\n====2003\u20132004: Continued individual success and injuries====\nIn early 2003, Cousins injured his ankle in a game against [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] but played on through five weeks of pain-killing injections.<ref name=\"beacham\">{{cite news |first=Digby |last=Beacham |title=Top Eagle dreams of soaring higher |work=Sunday Herald Sun |date=10 July 2005 |page=56}}</ref> In Round 15, 2004, he injured his back and missed six games. Cousins said, \"That injury is something that I got over and am probably no chance of getting a relapse... The other side to it is, because I have played 10 years of consistent AFL footy, I've probably got an older back than someone my age\".<ref name=\"beacham\" /> In Round 1, 2005, he dislocated a finger and missed one round after undergoing an operation.<ref name=\"beacham\" /> West Coast chief executive Trevor Nesbitt said, \"There's no doubt that he's at his best when under pressure and he's so resilient; he plays with injuries that other players wouldn't\".<ref name=\"beacham\" />\n\n====2004\u20132006: Brownlow Medal and Grand Final birth====\n[[File:Ben Cousins warming up, 2005 AFL Grand Final.jpg|thumb|upright|Cousins warming up before the 2005 Grand Final]]\nAfter Cousins played his 200th game in July 2005 he was given a \"rousing reception from 41,524 grateful fans\",<ref name=\"davutovic\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Davutovic |title=Situation normal as Cousins shines |work=The Sunday Times |location=Western Australia |date=17 July 2005 |page=89}}</ref> as video clips of his ten years at West Coast were shown at the end of the game. Cousins was \"possibly the highest-profile sportsman in Western Australia\",<ref name=\"beacham\" /> the youngest of the 10 West Coast players to reach 200 games and the 14th youngest in the history of the AFL/VFL.<ref name=\"beacham\" />\n\nCousins won the [[Brownlow Medal]], the AFL's highest individual player award, on 19 September 2005 with 20 votes, ahead of teammate [[Daniel Kerr]] on 19 votes and [[Nick Dal Santo]] on 18 votes.<ref name=\"hand\">{{cite news |first=Guy |last=Hand |title=AFL: Eagle Ben Cousins wins Brownlow Medal |work=Sports News |agency=Australian Associated Press |date=19 September 2005}}</ref> Cousins was the favourite to win with bookmakers, after five previous top-10 finishes.<ref name=\"hand\" /> He did not attend the award ceremony in Melbourne, remaining in Perth to prepare for West Coast's Grand Final match against [[Sydney Swans]] the following weekend.<ref name=\"hand\" /> His celebration was \"very quiet, I went over to the bar, bought the folks a bottle of champagne, had one lemonade and went up to the (hotel) room. I managed to get to sleep before midnight, which was a bonus.\"<ref name=\"gleeson\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Gleeson |title=The genuine article now wants a final victory |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=21 September 2005 |page=6}}</ref> West Coast's last training session in Perth before travelling to their first Grand Final game since 1994<ref name=\"hand\" /> was attended by 3,000 fans.<ref name=\"gleeson\" /> Trevor Nesbitt, West Coast's chief executive, said he expected that the combination of the team's Grand Final appearance, Cousins' Brownlow win, and [[Chris Judd]]'s Brownlow win in the previous year, would lead to a turnover of around $2&nbsp;million in club merchandise.<ref name=\"butler\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Butler |title=Brownlow double fires merchandise madness |work=The West Australian |date=22 September 2005 |page=9}}</ref> Nesbitt added:<ref name=\"butler\" />\n\n<blockquote>\"It's quite a special time for the club and it's probably worth $1&nbsp;million to WA footy as a minimum I would think... The performances of Chris and Ben assist us in raising more money for WA football and their contribution is just outstanding. They're marquee players and, apart from everything else that happens with them, they are extremely beneficial for all West Australians.\"</blockquote>\n\nWest Coast lost the [[2005 AFL Grand Final|2005 Grand Final]] to Sydney by four points, but as well as his Brownlow win, Cousins was awarded another West Coast Best and Fairest and the players' [[Leigh Matthews Trophy|Most Valuable Player]] award, with 159 votes compared to runner-up [[Matthew Pavlich]]'s 99 votes.<ref name=\"sheahan\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Sheahan |title=The buzz on Cuz |work=Herald Sun |date=1 October 2005 |page=40}}</ref> He was runner-up to [[Barry Hall]] in the coaches' player of the year award,<ref name=\"sheahan\" /> and in statistics, had 612 disposals, 24 goals, and ranked in the top five of the league in nine of the 12 categories.<ref name=\"sheahan\" />\n\n====2006\u20132007: Premiership Cup, off-field misconduct and captaincy resignation====\nIn February 2006, Cousins resigned his captaincy after an off-field incident where he fled a [[sobriety checkpoint|booze bus]].<ref name=\"chargeslikely\">{{cite news |title=Charge likely over booze-bus incident |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/charge-likely-over-boozebus-incident/2006/02/26/1140888738655.html |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=26 February 2006 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> In May 2006, he signed a new three-year contract with West Coast, and in September 2006, West Coast won the [[2006 AFL Grand Final|Grand Final]], defeating Sydney by one point.<ref name=\"highsandlows\">{{cite news |title=Ben Cousins highs and lows |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,22596692-2863,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=16 October 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> Cousins was suspended indefinitely by West Coast on 20 March 2007 after missing two training sessions.<ref name=\"atwar\">{{cite news |title=Teammates 'at war' over suspended AFL star |url=http://www.news.com.au/news/teammates-at-war-over-suspended-afl-star/story-fna7dq6e-1111113188494 |work=Fox Sports |date=20 March 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> It was later confirmed that Cousins had a [[substance abuse]] problem.<ref name=\"Heinrich\">{{cite news |first=Scott |last=Heinrich |title=Does new Tiger Ben Cousins have what it takes to change his stripes? |work=Fox Sports Australia |date=16 December 2008}}</ref>\n{{Wikinews|Ben Cousins sacked by West Coast in AFL drug scandal}}\nAfter returning from four weeks of rehabilitation in [[Malibu, California]] for substance abuse,<ref name=\"highsandlows\" /> Cousins was offered an amended contract by West Coast, rumoured to contain strict conditions such as repaying the cost of rehab and undertaking regular drug tests.<ref>{{cite news |first=Caroline |last=Wilson |title=Cousins' contract row looms |url=http://www.realfooty.com.au/articles/2007/06/12/1181414299396.html |work=Real Footy |date=13 June 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> On 29 June 2007, Cousins was given clearance by the AFL to resume training with the West Coast Eagles, which he did the following Monday.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hawks beat Magpies in a classic |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Hawks-beat-Magpies-in-a-classic/2007/07/01/1183228959841.html |work=The Age |date=1 July 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008 |location=Australia}}</ref> However, he injured a [[hamstring]] in training,<ref>{{cite news |first=Jon |last=Pierik |title=Cousins comeback hamstrung |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,22028084-23211,00.html |work=Fox Sports |date=6 July 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> delaying his comeback until West Coast's home game against Sydney on 21 July at [[Subiaco Oval]]. He gained 38 disposals and six marks in the game,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cousins returns, Eagles down Swans |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Cousins-classy-as-Eagles-down-Swans/2007/07/21/1184560115356.html |work=The Age |date=21 July 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008 |location=Australia}}</ref> inspiring West Coast's win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cousins stars in Eagles comeback |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/07/21/1984716.htm |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=21 July 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n====2007\u20132008: Drug possession arrest, delisted by West Coast Eagles and 12-month AFL ban====\nOn 16 October 2007, Cousins' car was stopped in [[Northbridge, Western Australia|Northbridge]] and searched.  He was arrested for drug possession and refusing to submit to a blood test.  The Eagles sacked him the next day, which meant that he was no longer a registered AFL player.<ref name=\"sacked\" /> On 19 November, he was banned from playing senior football for 12 months by the AFL Commission for \"bringing the game into disrepute\",<ref name=\"disrepute\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Cousins slapped with 12-month ban |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/11/19/2095135.htm |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=19 November 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> and was formally delisted by West Coast on 30 November.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Burgan |title=Cousins now officially no longer an Eagle |url=http://afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=53954 |publisher=Australian Football League |date=30 November 2008 |accessdate=21 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103000925/http://afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=53954 |archive-date=3 January 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Eagles officials said that he would never appear in an Eagles guernsey again, and AFL CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] said it would be \"extremely difficult\" for him to ever return to the AFL.<ref name=\"sacked\" />\n\n===Richmond Tigers===\n====2008\u20132010: Career renewal at Richmond Tigers and retirement====\nIn November 2008, the AFL Commission cleared Cousins to play AFL football in 2009. The Commission ruled that Cousins must submit to regular [[drug tests]], including urine testing up to three times per week and hair testing up to four times annually.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Pinkney |title=Ben Cousins cleared by AFL Commission after drugs scandal |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24669579-11088,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=18 November 2008 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref> Cousins attended drug testing in early November with no body hair long enough to sample.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Noakes, C |author2=Niall, J. |title=Cousins on notice over hair length |url=http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/cousins-on-notice-over-hair-length/2008/11/20/1226770550394.html |work=Real Footy |date=20 November 2008 |accessdate=21 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nSeveral teams showed an interest in [[Draft (sports)|drafting]] Cousins for 2009, including [[Collingwood Football Club]], [[St Kilda Football Club]] and [[Brisbane Lions]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Rielly |title=Brisbane the last hope for Ben Cousins |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24707524-601,00.html |work=The Australian |date=26 November 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> Collingwood sent a [[private investigator]] to Perth to follow Cousins for several days. After meeting with Victorian Chief Commissioner of Police [[Christine Nixon]] in October 2008, Collingwood announced that they would not draft Cousins.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ainsworth |first1=Michelle |last2=Mawby |first2=Nathan |title=Eddie McGuire reveals call to Christine Nixon about Ben Cousins |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24514049-662,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> In November, after reviewing Cousins and consulting stakeholders for five months, St Kilda said they would not draft him.<ref>{{cite news |title=St Kilda shun Ben Cousins |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24707870-5001023,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=25 November 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> The day before the national draft, Brisbane issued a media release that said they would not be drafting Cousins.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brisbane Lions say they don't want Cousins |url=http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/brisbane-lions-say-they-dont-want-cousins/2008/11/28/1227491826524.html |work=Real Footy |date=29 November 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218220301/http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/brisbane-lions-say-they-dont-want-cousins/2008/11/28/1227491826524.html |archivedate=18 December 2008  |url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 November 2008, Cousins was not selected in the [[AFL National Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Watts top draft pick, Cousins ignored |url=http://news.theage.com.au/sport/watts-top-draft-pick-cousins-ignored-20081129-6n8s.html |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=29 November 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206072617/http://news.theage.com.au/sport/watts-top-draft-pick-cousins-ignored-20081129-6n8s.html |archivedate=6 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Richmond Carlton MCG 2009.jpg|thumb|\"The man who sold out the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\": Cousins' AFL return helped break the attendance record for a Richmond versus Carlton match.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-03-24/blues-tigers-mcg-clash-sold-out/1629216 \"Blues-Tigers MCG clash sold out\"] (24 March 2009), ''ABC News''. Retrieved 9 July 2018.</ref><ref>Wilson, Caroline (26 March 2009). [https://www.theage.com.au/news/news/the-man-who-sold-out-the-mcg/2009/03/25/1237656995732.html \"The man who sold out the MCG\"], ''The Age''. Retrieved 9 July 2018.</ref>]]\nAhead of the [[AFL Pre-season Draft]] in December 2008, Richmond Football Club approached the AFL Commission for approval to move injured senior player [[Graham Polak]] to its [[rookie list]] in order to obtain a second draft pick in the pre-season draft, which it said it would use to select Cousins.<ref>{{cite news |first=Courtney |last=Walsh |title=Richmond's risky bid for Ben Cousins |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24783691-5012432,00.html |work=The Australian |date=11 December 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220072303/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0%2C25197%2C24783691-5012432%2C00.html |archivedate=20 December 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The AFL Commission had given approval to [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] two years earlier to do similar with [[Adam Ramanauskas]] during his battle with cancer. The commission, with the support of the AFLPA and most of the clubs, denied Richmond's request.<ref>{{cite news |title=League denies Tigers' rookie plans for Polak |url=http://afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=70846 |publisher=Australian Football League |date=15 December 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218005720/http://www.afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=70846 |archivedate=18 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Richmond selected Cousins with its only Pre-season Draft selection (#6 overall) on 16 December.<ref name=\"backflip\">{{cite news |author1=Flower, W |author2=Schulz, M |author3=Barrett, D |author4=Wright, A. |title=Richmond backflip gives Cousins a lifeline |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/richmond-recruit-ben-cousins/story-e6frg12c-1111118330270 |work=PerthNow |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531105501/http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/richmond-recruit-ben-cousins/story-e6frg12c-1111118330270 |archive-date=31 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Following this Richmond received an influx of new club members<ref name=\"backflip\" /> and Cousins trained with the team the following day in front of a crowd of around 2,000.<ref>{{cite news |first=Katherine |last=Firkin |title=Ben Cousins expresses his gratitude to Richmond |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,24813003-19742,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220100221/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0%2C26576%2C24813003-19742%2C00.html |archivedate=20 December 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In Richmond's Round 1 game against [[Carlton Football Club|Carlton]] on 26 March, Cousins strained his [[hamstring]] during the final quarter.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Sheridan |title=Cousins, Raines out for month |url=http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/rfnews/cousins-raines-out-for-month/2009/03/27/1237657151097.html |work=Real Footy |date=28 March 2009 |accessdate=10 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331114734/http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/rfnews/cousins-raines-out-for-month/2009/03/27/1237657151097.html |archivedate=31 March 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He played a game with the [[Coburg Football Club]] in the [[Victorian Football League]] before returning to the AFL in Round 7 against [[Brisbane Lions|Brisbane]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Cousins |title=I thought someone might clock me: Ben Cousins |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,25449876-19742,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=9 May 2009 |accessdate=10 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511141121/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0%2C21985%2C25449876-19742%2C00.html |archivedate=11 May 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Glenn |last=McFarlane |title=Willing Ben Cousins shines |url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25454854-19742,00.html |work=Herald Sun |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=10 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514052216/http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0%2C26576%2C25454854-19742%2C00.html |archivedate=14 May 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2010, after weeks of speculation by the media, Cousins announced his retirement in front of his family and huge crowd. During the speech, he thanked everyone who had assisted him during his career, acknowledged his encounters with drugs and the law, and apologised to his family for the situation he had put them in:<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sheahan |first=Sheahan |title=Hard road for Ben Cousins |newspaper=The Herald Sun |date=21 August 2010 |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/afl/hard-road-for-ben-cousins/story-e6frepf6-1225907998440 |accessdate=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n<blockquote>I'll always regret what I've put my family through. There's a lot of shame and regret. People wonder why I haven't broken down or shed a tear (in public). My tears are something that I hold close to me; they're for me and my family.</blockquote>\n\n==Statistics==\n:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/B/Ben_Cousins.html |title=AFL Tables \u2013 Ben Cousins \u2013 Stats \u2013 Statistics |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|\n| Led the league for the season only\n|-\n| style=\"background:#b7e71