\"9\" | {{dts|2020|03|23}}{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|EST}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Estonia]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Finland]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ISL}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Iceland]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LVA}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Latvia]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Lithuania]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Norway]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|POL}} [[Disney XD (Poland)|Poland]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Disney XD (Scandinavia)|Sweden]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|POR}} [[Disney Channel (Portuguese TV channel)|Portugal]]\n| scope=\"row\" | {{dts|2020|04}}{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Disney Channel (Turkish TV channel)|Turkey]]\n| scope=\"row\" | {{dts|2020|05}}{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n''Amphibia'' received a positive reception from critics. ''[[Common Sense Media]]''{{'}}s Emily Ashby praised the series for its characters and themes, writing that \"Sprig and Anne's adventures are a joy to behold, mostly thanks to their delightfully compatible personalities and the sweet friendship that develops between them\" and that \"the story illustrates issues like [[bullying]] and [[emotional manipulation]] in ways that will resonate with kids and tweens and can prompt discussions about the topics\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/amphibia|title=Amphibia TV Review|website=Common Sense Media|language=en}}</ref> Bekah Burbank of ''LaughingPlace.com'' praised the series' ability to balance its humor and its terror elements, as well as its pacing, characters, and animation, stating that \"''Amphibia'' is clever and goofy with plenty of jokes to keep kids laughing and just enough scary content to hold their attention. The show moves quickly and is broken into two 11-minute episodes that, at least for the premiere, form one complete chapter. The animation is bouncy and colorful and the characters are a delight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laughingplace.com/w/articles/2019/06/15/tv-review-disney-channels-amphibia/|title=TV Review: Disney Channel's \"Amphibia\"|website=LaughingPlace.com|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''{{'}}s Dave Trumbore gave the series' first two episodes a 4 stars rating, feeling that they \"[served] as a great introduction to the series\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/amphibia-review-disneys-frog-out-of-water-series-delivers-compelling-characters/|title='Amphibia' Review: Disney's Frog-Out-of-Water Series Delivers Compelling Characters|website=[[Collider]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://disneynow.go.com/shows/amphibia/}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt8050740}}\n\n{{Disney Channel Original Series}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney Television Animation]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about frogs and toads]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Thai American]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amphibia_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Ronald Bailey", "text_new": "{{short description|American libertarian science writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image         = File:Ronald Bailey by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = Photograph of Ronald Bailey\n| caption       = Ronald Bailey in 2015\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   =\n| resting_place =\n| occupation    = Science correspondent\n| language      = English\n| nationality   = American\n| ethnicity     =\n| citizenship   = United States\n| education     = B.A.\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Virginia]]\n| period        =\n| genre         =\n| subject       = [[Climate change (general concept)|Climate Change]], [[Global warming|Global Warming]], [[Economics]], [[Ecology]], [[Biotechnology]]\n| movement      =\n| notableworks  = Eco-scam: The False Prophets of Ecological Apocalypse.\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| children      =\n| relatives     =\n| influences    =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Ronald Bailey''' (born November 23, 1953) is an American [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]]  [[Science journalism|science writer]]. He has written or edited several books on [[economics]], [[ecology]], and [[biotechnology]].<ref name= \"reasonbio\">{{cite web |title= Ronald Bailey: Science Correspondent |url= http://reason.com/people/ronald-bailey/articles |work= [[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] website |publisher= [[Reason Foundation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBailey was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], and raised in [[Washington County, Virginia]]. He lives in [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], with his wife Pamela.<ref name=\"reasonbio\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nBailey attended the [[University of Virginia]], where he earned a B.A. in philosophy and economics in 1976.<ref name=\"secrets\">{{cite web |title= Factsheet: Ronald Bailey | url= http://www.exxonsecrets.org/html/personfactsheet.php?id=11 |work= exxonsecrets.org |publisher= [[Greenpeace]] |accessdate= 2013-07-15}}</ref> He worked briefly as an economist for the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]]. From 1987 to 1990 he contributed articles to [[Forbes]].<ref name= \"reasonbio\"/> Bailey worked as a reporter for ''The Tico Times'' in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica]] during 1990 and 1991.<ref name= \"F&RaboutRB\"/> His articles and reviews have appeared in national newspapers and magazines and have been selected for inclusion in [[The Best American Science Writing]] anthology series.<ref name= \"reasonbio\"/><ref name=\"PinkerFolger2004\">{{cite book|editor1-first=Steven |editor1-last=Pinker|editor2-first=Tim |editor2-last=Folger|title=The Best American Science And Nature Writing 2004|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FbVUMgEACAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=978-0-618-24697-7}}</ref> Bailey was the founding producer of the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] series [[Think Tank]] and has produced or co-produced several series and documentaries for PBS television and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] News.<ref name= \"F&RaboutRB\">{{cite web |title= About Ronald Bailey |url= https://www.pbs.org/faithandreason/stdweb/bailey.html |work= Faith & Reason website |publisher= [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]}}</ref><ref name= \"F&Rguide\">{{cite web | title= Faith & Reason: Educators Guide |url= https://www.pbs.org/faithandreason/stdweb/guide.html |last= Wertheim |first= Margaret |publisher= New River Media and Five Continents Music}}</ref> Since 1997 he has been a science correspondent for ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine.<ref name= \"reasonstaff\">{{cite web |title= Staff |url= http://reason.com/staff |work= Reason website}}</ref>  Bailey was the 1993 Warren T. Brookes Fellow in Environmental Journalism at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] (CEI).<ref name= \"CEI\">{{cite web |title= The Warren T. Brookes Journalism Fellowship |url= http://cei.org/warrenbrookes |work= [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] website |accessdate= 2013-07-15}}</ref>\n\nHe has lectured at [[Harvard University]], [[Rutgers University]], [[McGill University]], [[University of Alaska]], [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]], the [[Cato Institute]], the Instituto de Libertad y Desarrollo (Chile), and the [[American Enterprise Institute]]. A column he wrote in 2004, \"The battle for your brain\" received a Southern California Journalism award from the Los Angeles Press Club and was included in the book, ''The Best of American Science and Nature Writing 2004''.<ref name=\"PinkerFolger2004\" /><ref>{{cite web |title= 2004 Southern California Journalism Award Winners |url= http://lapressclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/2004-Southern-California-Journalism-Award-Winners1.pdf |accessdate= 2013-07-28 |website= Los Angeles Press Club website |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131102052302/http://lapressclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/2004-Southern-California-Journalism-Award-Winners1.pdf |archivedate= 2013-11-02 }}</ref> Bailey testified before a congressional sub-committee in 2004 on, \"The Impact of Science on Public Policy.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources Oversight Hearing on \"The Impact of Science on Public Policy.\" |url= http://naturalresources.house.gov/calendar/eventsingle.aspx?EventID=163230 |publisher= US House of Representatives, Committee on Natural Resources |accessdate= 2013-07-28 |date= 2004-02-04}}</ref> In 2006 he was on the shortlist of nominees of \"personalities who have made the most significant contributions to biotech in the last ten years\" compiled by the editors of [[Nature Biotechnology]].<ref name=\"shortlist\">{{cite journal |title= Who's who in biotech |last1= Jayaraman |first1= KS |last2= Lou\u00ebt |first2= S |last3= Powell |first3= K |first4= J |last4= Ransom |first5= C |last5= Sheridan |first6= B |last6= Vastag |first7= E |last7= Wa |display-authors= 4 |journal= [[Nature Biotechnology]] |volume= 24 |issue= 3 |date= March 2006 |url= http://www.systemsbiology.org/download/BitechWhosWho.pdf |accessdate= 2013-07-15 |page= 298 |doi= 10.1038/nbt0306-291 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150606063854/http://www.systemsbiology.org/download/BitechWhosWho.pdf |archivedate= 2015-06-06 |pmid=16525392}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nIn 1989, in an article<ref name=Bailey-1989>{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=Ronald|title=Dr Doom|journal=Forbes|date=16 October 1989}}</ref> in ''Forbes'', Bailey wrote a \"...sneering attack ...\" on [[Jay Forrester]], the father of [[system dynamics]]. In the article he described the book, ''[[The Limits to Growth]]'' (LTG) as \"as wrong-headed as it is possible to be.\" Bailey said that, \"''Limits to Growth'' predicted that at 1972 rates of growth the world would run out of gold by 1981, mercury by 1985, tin by 1987, zinc by 1990, petroleum by 1992, copper, lead and natural gas by 1993.\"<ref name=Bailey-1989/>{{RP|45}} According to physical chemist and energy expert, [[Ugo Bardi]], \"...Bailey's accusations are just plain wrong.\" In 1993 Bailey repeated his accusations in his book, ''Ecoscam''. In it, he claimed that none of the projections of the 1972 ''LTG'' study turned out to be correct.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bardi|first1=Ugo|title=Cassandra's Curse: how \"The Limits to Growth\" was demonized|url=http://www.sustainable.soltechdesigns.com/cassandra.html|website=The Oil Drum Europe|accessdate=2 December 2017|date=9 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1993 book, ''Ecoscam'', Bailey wrote, \"Despite a great deal of continuing scientific uncertainty, it appears that CFCs do contribute to the creation of the Antarctic ozone hole and perhaps a tiny amount of global ozone depletion. ... [I]t makes sense to phase out the use of CFCs.\" When ''[[Science (magazine)|Science]]'' reported in July 2016 that the ozone layer was restoring itself after CFCs were banned, Bailey wrote, \"Since atmospheric pollution presents significant barriers to assigning property rights, I concluded that the international treaty banning CFCs was the appropriate response.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://reason.com/blog/2016/07/01/ozone-hole-over-antarctica-is-closing-re | first=Ronald | last=Bailey | title=Ozone Hole Over Antarctica Is Closing, Reports Science | work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] | date=July 1, 2016 | accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe position taken in his 1995 book ''The True State of the Planet'' has been described as \"growth forever\" or \"Promethean\" arguing for unrestrained exploitation based on assumptions of unending nature, value derived exclusively from man's changes to material, and exceptional human resourcefulness.<ref name= \"Milne2009\">{{cite journal |title= Words not actions! The ideological role of sustainable development reporting |url= https://research.mbs.ac.uk/accounting-finance/Portals/0/docs/2008/WordsnotActionsTheIdeologicalRoleofSustainableDevelopmentReporting.pdf |last1= Milne |first1= MJ |last2= Tregidga |first2= H |last3= Walton |first3= S |journal= [[Accounting, Auditing & Accountability Journal]] |volume= 22 |issue= 8 |doi= 10.1108/09513570910999292 |year=2009 |pages= 1211\u20131257}}</ref> His follow-up book ''Earth Report 2000'' was recognized for being among the works of established authors \"who have argued that past and present widely accepted visions of environmental deterioration and disaster ... have little or no basis in fact.\"<ref name= \"Henderson2001\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Henderson | first1 = David  |ssrn=681168 | title = Misguided Virtue | year = 2005 }}</ref> Citing these two books, Holt, Pressman and Spash describe the CEI as believing, \"technology will solve all environmental problems and that present environmental dilemmas are simply a necessary outcome of much needed economic growth.\"<ref name=\"HoltPressman2009\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Holt|editor1-first=RPF|editor2-last=Pressman|editor2-first=S|editor3-last=Spash|editor3-first=CL|title=Post Keynesian and Ecological Economics: Confronting Environmental Issues|year=2009|publisher=Edward Elgar|location=Northampton, MA|isbn=978-1-84980-208-6|page=109}}</ref>\n\nBailey has described himself as a \"[[libertarian transhumanism|libertarian transhumanist]].\" He explains this in his book ''Liberation Biology''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.innovationwatch.com/books/bks_1591022274.htm |title= Liberation Biology: The Scientific and Moral Case for the Biotech Revolution |format= book review |work= Innovation Watch |archivedate= 2006-05-12 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060512211644/http://www.innovationwatch.com/books/bks_1591022274.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Bailey said that new data convinced him that the earth is definitely warming and that the likely cause is human activity. He has endorsed a [[carbon tax]] as one possible solution.<ref>http://americasfuture.org/i-want-to-believe/</ref> He has stated in the article \"Global Warming&nbsp;\u2014 Not Worse Than We Thought, But Bad Enough\":\n\n<blockquote>Details like sea level rise will continue to be debated by researchers, but if the debate over whether or not humanity is contributing to global warming wasn't over before, it is now&nbsp;... as the new IPCC Summary makes clear, climate change Pollyannaism is no longer looking very tenable.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first=Ronald |url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/118479.html |title= Global Warming&nbsp;\u2014 Not Worse Than We Thought, But Bad Enough |magazine= Reason |date= 2007-02-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nBailey is critical of [[Al Gore]] and [[An Inconvenient Truth|his film]] about global warming, writing, \"On balance Gore gets it more right than wrong on the science (we'll leave the policy stuff to another time), but he undercuts his message by becoming the opposite of a global warming denier. He's a global warming exaggerator.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.reason.com/rb/rb061606.shtml |title= An Inconvenient Truth |last= Bailey |first= Ronald |magazine= Reason |date= 2006-06-16 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061227062020/http://www.reason.com/rb/rb061606.shtml |archivedate= 2006-12-27 }}</ref>\n\nBailey voted for [[George W. Bush]] in both [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]] and [[2004 United States presidential election|2004]], a fact which he later wrote made him \"disheartened and ashamed.\"<ref name=vote>{{cite news |url= http://reason.com/archives/2008/10/29/whos-getting-your-vote/singlepage |title= Who's Getting Your Vote? Reason's 2008 presidential poll |magazine=Reason |date= 2008-10-29}}</ref> In [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]], he voted for [[Barack Obama]] because he felt that \"[t]he [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] must be punished and punished hard.\"<ref name=vote/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n===Authored===\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=Eco-scam: The False Prophets of Ecological Apocalypse|year=1993|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-10971-4 |authormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=Liberation Biology: The Scientific and Moral Case for the Biotech Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/liberationbiolog0000bail|url-access=registration|year=2005|publisher=Prometheus|isbn=978-1-61592-169-0|authormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=The End of Doom: Environmental Renewal in the Twenty-first Century|year=2015|publisher=Thomas Dunne Books|isbn=9781250057679|authormask=0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/endofdoomenviron0000bail}}\n\n===Edited===\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=True State of the Planet|year=1995|publisher=Free Press|isbn=978-0-02-874010-2|editormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=Earth Report 2000: Revisiting the True State of the Planet|year=1999|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=978-0-07-134260-5|editormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=Global Warming and Other Eco-myths: How the Environmental Movement Uses False Science to Scare Us to Death|year=2002|publisher=Forum|isbn=978-0-7615-3660-4|editormask=0}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transhumanism#Threats to morality and democracy|''Brave New World'' argument]]\n* [[Transhumanism#Trivialization of human identity|''Enough'' argument]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|ronaldbailey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Ronald}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University people]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Washington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American transhumanists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Competitive Enterprise Institute]]\n[[Category:People from Charlottesville, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American libertarian science writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image         = File:Ronald Bailey by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = Photograph of Ronald Bailey\n| caption       = Ronald Bailey in 2015\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   =\n| resting_place =\n| occupation    = Science correspondent\n| language      = English\n| nationality   = American\n| ethnicity     =\n| citizenship   = United States\n| education     = B.A.\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Virginia]]\n| period        =\n| genre         =\n| subject       = [[Climate Change]], [[Global Warming]], [[Economics]], [[Ecology]], [[Biotechnology]]\n| movement      =\n| notableworks  = Eco-scam: The False Prophets of Ecological Apocalypse.\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| children      =\n| relatives     =\n| influences    =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Ronald Bailey''' (born November 23, 1953) is an American [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]]  [[Science journalism|science writer]]. He has written or edited several books on [[economics]], [[ecology]], and [[biotechnology]].<ref name= \"reasonbio\">{{cite web |title= Ronald Bailey: Science Correspondent |url= http://reason.com/people/ronald-bailey/articles |work= [[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] website |publisher= [[Reason Foundation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBailey was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], and raised in [[Washington County, Virginia]]. He lives in [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], with his wife Pamela.<ref name=\"reasonbio\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nBailey attended the [[University of Virginia]], where he earned a B.A. in philosophy and economics in 1976.<ref name=\"secrets\">{{cite web |title= Factsheet: Ronald Bailey | url= http://www.exxonsecrets.org/html/personfactsheet.php?id=11 |work= exxonsecrets.org |publisher= [[Greenpeace]] |accessdate= 2013-07-15}}</ref> He worked briefly as an economist for the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]]. From 1987 to 1990 he contributed articles to [[Forbes]].<ref name= \"reasonbio\"/> Bailey worked as a reporter for ''The Tico Times'' in [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica]] during 1990 and 1991.<ref name= \"F&RaboutRB\"/> His articles and reviews have appeared in national newspapers and magazines and have been selected for inclusion in [[The Best American Science Writing]] anthology series.<ref name= \"reasonbio\"/><ref name=\"PinkerFolger2004\">{{cite book|editor1-first=Steven |editor1-last=Pinker|editor2-first=Tim |editor2-last=Folger|title=The Best American Science And Nature Writing 2004|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FbVUMgEACAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=978-0-618-24697-7}}</ref> Bailey was the founding producer of the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] series [[Think Tank]] and has produced or co-produced several series and documentaries for PBS television and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] News.<ref name= \"F&RaboutRB\">{{cite web |title= About Ronald Bailey |url= https://www.pbs.org/faithandreason/stdweb/bailey.html |work= Faith & Reason website |publisher= [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]}}</ref><ref name= \"F&Rguide\">{{cite web | title= Faith & Reason: Educators Guide |url= https://www.pbs.org/faithandreason/stdweb/guide.html |last= Wertheim |first= Margaret |publisher= New River Media and Five Continents Music}}</ref> Since 1997 he has been a science correspondent for ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine.<ref name= \"reasonstaff\">{{cite web |title= Staff |url= http://reason.com/staff |work= Reason website}}</ref>  Bailey was the 1993 Warren T. Brookes Fellow in Environmental Journalism at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] (CEI).<ref name= \"CEI\">{{cite web |title= The Warren T. Brookes Journalism Fellowship |url= http://cei.org/warrenbrookes |work= [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] website |accessdate= 2013-07-15}}</ref>\n\nHe has lectured at [[Harvard University]], [[Rutgers University]], [[McGill University]], [[University of Alaska]], [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec]], the [[Cato Institute]], the Instituto de Libertad y Desarrollo (Chile), and the [[American Enterprise Institute]]. A column he wrote in 2004, \"The battle for your brain\" received a Southern California Journalism award from the Los Angeles Press Club and was included in the book, ''The Best of American Science and Nature Writing 2004''.<ref name=\"PinkerFolger2004\" /><ref>{{cite web |title= 2004 Southern California Journalism Award Winners |url= http://lapressclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/2004-Southern-California-Journalism-Award-Winners1.pdf |accessdate= 2013-07-28 |website= Los Angeles Press Club website |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131102052302/http://lapressclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/2004-Southern-California-Journalism-Award-Winners1.pdf |archivedate= 2013-11-02 }}</ref> Bailey testified before a congressional sub-committee in 2004 on, \"The Impact of Science on Public Policy.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources Oversight Hearing on \"The Impact of Science on Public Policy.\" |url= http://naturalresources.house.gov/calendar/eventsingle.aspx?EventID=163230 |publisher= US House of Representatives, Committee on Natural Resources |accessdate= 2013-07-28 |date= 2004-02-04}}</ref> In 2006 he was on the shortlist of nominees of \"personalities who have made the most significant contributions to biotech in the last ten years\" compiled by the editors of [[Nature Biotechnology]].<ref name=\"shortlist\">{{cite journal |title= Who's who in biotech |last1= Jayaraman |first1= KS |last2= Lou\u00ebt |first2= S |last3= Powell |first3= K |first4= J |last4= Ransom |first5= C |last5= Sheridan |first6= B |last6= Vastag |first7= E |last7= Wa |display-authors= 4 |journal= [[Nature Biotechnology]] |volume= 24 |issue= 3 |date= March 2006 |url= http://www.systemsbiology.org/download/BitechWhosWho.pdf |accessdate= 2013-07-15 |page= 298 |doi= 10.1038/nbt0306-291 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150606063854/http://www.systemsbiology.org/download/BitechWhosWho.pdf |archivedate= 2015-06-06 |pmid=16525392}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nIn 1989, in an article<ref name=Bailey-1989>{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=Ronald|title=Dr Doom|journal=Forbes|date=16 October 1989}}</ref> in ''Forbes'', Bailey wrote a \"...sneering attack ...\" on [[Jay Forrester]], the father of [[system dynamics]]. In the article he described the book, ''[[The Limits to Growth]]'' (LTG) as \"as wrong-headed as it is possible to be.\" Bailey said that, \"''Limits to Growth'' predicted that at 1972 rates of growth the world would run out of gold by 1981, mercury by 1985, tin by 1987, zinc by 1990, petroleum by 1992, copper, lead and natural gas by 1993.\"<ref name=Bailey-1989/>{{RP|45}} According to physical chemist and energy expert, [[Ugo Bardi]], \"...Bailey's accusations are just plain wrong.\" In 1993 Bailey repeated his accusations in his book, ''Ecoscam''. In it, he claimed that none of the projections of the 1972 ''LTG'' study turned out to be correct.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bardi|first1=Ugo|title=Cassandra's Curse: how \"The Limits to Growth\" was demonized|url=http://www.sustainable.soltechdesigns.com/cassandra.html|website=The Oil Drum Europe|accessdate=2 December 2017|date=9 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1993 book, ''Ecoscam'', Bailey wrote, \"Despite a great deal of continuing scientific uncertainty, it appears that CFCs do contribute to the creation of the Antarctic ozone hole and perhaps a tiny amount of global ozone depletion. ... [I]t makes sense to phase out the use of CFCs.\" When ''[[Science (magazine)|Science]]'' reported in July 2016 that the ozone layer was restoring itself after CFCs were banned, Bailey wrote, \"Since atmospheric pollution presents significant barriers to assigning property rights, I concluded that the international treaty banning CFCs was the appropriate response.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://reason.com/blog/2016/07/01/ozone-hole-over-antarctica-is-closing-re | first=Ronald | last=Bailey | title=Ozone Hole Over Antarctica Is Closing, Reports Science | work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] | date=July 1, 2016 | accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe position taken in his 1995 book ''The True State of the Planet'' has been described as \"growth forever\" or \"Promethean\" arguing for unrestrained exploitation based on assumptions of unending nature, value derived exclusively from man's changes to material, and exceptional human resourcefulness.<ref name= \"Milne2009\">{{cite journal |title= Words not actions! The ideological role of sustainable development reporting |url= https://research.mbs.ac.uk/accounting-finance/Portals/0/docs/2008/WordsnotActionsTheIdeologicalRoleofSustainableDevelopmentReporting.pdf |last1= Milne |first1= MJ |last2= Tregidga |first2= H |last3= Walton |first3= S |journal= [[Accounting, Auditing & Accountability Journal]] |volume= 22 |issue= 8 |doi= 10.1108/09513570910999292 |year=2009 |pages= 1211\u20131257}}</ref> His follow-up book ''Earth Report 2000'' was recognized for being among the works of established authors \"who have argued that past and present widely accepted visions of environmental deterioration and disaster ... have little or no basis in fact.\"<ref name= \"Henderson2001\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Henderson | first1 = David  |ssrn=681168 | title = Misguided Virtue | year = 2005 }}</ref> Citing these two books, Holt, Pressman and Spash describe the CEI as believing, \"technology will solve all environmental problems and that present environmental dilemmas are simply a necessary outcome of much needed economic growth.\"<ref name=\"HoltPressman2009\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Holt|editor1-first=RPF|editor2-last=Pressman|editor2-first=S|editor3-last=Spash|editor3-first=CL|title=Post Keynesian and Ecological Economics: Confronting Environmental Issues|year=2009|publisher=Edward Elgar|location=Northampton, MA|isbn=978-1-84980-208-6|page=109}}</ref>\n\nBailey has described himself as a \"[[libertarian transhumanism|libertarian transhumanist]].\" He explains this in his book ''Liberation Biology''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.innovationwatch.com/books/bks_1591022274.htm |title= Liberation Biology: The Scientific and Moral Case for the Biotech Revolution |format= book review |work= Innovation Watch |archivedate= 2006-05-12 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060512211644/http://www.innovationwatch.com/books/bks_1591022274.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Bailey said that new data convinced him that the earth is definitely warming and that the likely cause is human activity. He has endorsed a [[carbon tax]] as one possible solution.<ref>http://americasfuture.org/i-want-to-believe/</ref> He has stated in the article \"Global Warming&nbsp;\u2014 Not Worse Than We Thought, But Bad Enough\":\n\n<blockquote>Details like sea level rise will continue to be debated by researchers, but if the debate over whether or not humanity is contributing to global warming wasn't over before, it is now&nbsp;... as the new IPCC Summary makes clear, climate change Pollyannaism is no longer looking very tenable.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first=Ronald |url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/118479.html |title= Global Warming&nbsp;\u2014 Not Worse Than We Thought, But Bad Enough |magazine= Reason |date= 2007-02-02}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nBailey is critical of [[Al Gore]] and [[An Inconvenient Truth|his film]] about global warming, writing, \"On balance Gore gets it more right than wrong on the science (we'll leave the policy stuff to another time), but he undercuts his message by becoming the opposite of a global warming denier. He's a global warming exaggerator.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.reason.com/rb/rb061606.shtml |title= An Inconvenient Truth |last= Bailey |first= Ronald |magazine= Reason |date= 2006-06-16 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061227062020/http://www.reason.com/rb/rb061606.shtml |archivedate= 2006-12-27 }}</ref>\n\nBailey voted for [[George W. Bush]] in both [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]] and [[2004 United States presidential election|2004]], a fact which he later wrote made him \"disheartened and ashamed.\"<ref name=vote>{{cite news |url= http://reason.com/archives/2008/10/29/whos-getting-your-vote/singlepage |title= Who's Getting Your Vote? Reason's 2008 presidential poll |magazine=Reason |date= 2008-10-29}}</ref> In [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]], he voted for [[Barack Obama]] because he felt that \"[t]he [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] must be punished and punished hard.\"<ref name=vote/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n===Authored===\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=Eco-scam: The False Prophets of Ecological Apocalypse|year=1993|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-10971-4 |authormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=Liberation Biology: The Scientific and Moral Case for the Biotech Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/liberationbiolog0000bail|url-access=registration|year=2005|publisher=Prometheus|isbn=978-1-61592-169-0|authormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Ronald Bailey|title=The End of Doom: Environmental Renewal in the Twenty-first Century|year=2015|publisher=Thomas Dunne Books|isbn=9781250057679|authormask=0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/endofdoomenviron0000bail}}\n\n===Edited===\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=True State of the Planet|year=1995|publisher=Free Press|isbn=978-0-02-874010-2|editormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=Earth Report 2000: Revisiting the True State of the Planet|year=1999|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=978-0-07-134260-5|editormask=0}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Ronald Bailey|title=Global Warming and Other Eco-myths: How the Environmental Movement Uses False Science to Scare Us to Death|year=2002|publisher=Forum|isbn=978-0-7615-3660-4|editormask=0}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transhumanism#Threats to morality and democracy|''Brave New World'' argument]]\n* [[Transhumanism#Trivialization of human identity|''Enough'' argument]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|ronaldbailey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n